{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689913/1958020301/0370.xml":{"full_text":"Page 6\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN Monday, February 1951\nThe Key West Citizen\nPublished Sunday Morning and Every Week Day Afternoon,\nExcept Saturday\nNORMAN D. ARTMAN Editor Publisher\nMARGARET FORESMAN City Editor\nCLAY RILEV Advertising Manager\nRAYFORD ROBERTS Circulation Manager\nPERCY CL\u2019RRY Mechanical Superintendent\n1\nMEMBER OF ASSOCIATED PRESS\nEntered at Key West, Florida as\nSecond Class Matter\nCARRIER SUBSCRIPTION RATES\n1 Year $15.66\nMonth* 7.80\n1 Month 1.30\n1 Week .30\nMAIL RATES\n1 Year 118.80\nMonths 7.80\nI Months 4.50\n1 Month 1.75\n(No weekly mall subscriptions Accepted)\nNATIONAL ADVERTISING REPRESENTATIVES:\nTHEIS SIMPSON, CO., INC.\n1 E. 54th St., New York 22. N. Y.\nBranch Offices In Principal Cities\n\"Looser\" Money Policies\nBrighten Business Outlook\nIn recent weeks, the Federal Reserve board of gov\nemors\u2014the people who set the interest rates on money\nf loaned to banks and similar institutions\u2014have made\nseveral moves to \u201cloosen up\u201d the tight money situation.\nThe moves they\u2019ve made have cleared the way for\neasier, cheaper borrowing and investing by big com\npanies and wealthy individuals. These new policies\u2014\ncoupled with bigger defense spending by the federal\ngovernment\u2014will probably help a lot to get the nation\u2019s\nbusiness going full swing again.\nThe effects may not be felt right away.\nIt may take a few months.\nBut unless some other unforeseen thing happens\nto put the brakes on business, the men on the street in\ntowns across the country should find jobs easier to get\nand paychecks a little healthier before the end of 1958.\nFor when companies can borrow easily and cheaply to\nput in new equipment or build new plants, when build\ners can get hold of money to put up new houses, w'hen\nbig corporations can obtain loans, then business usually\nstarts to move. And when business starts moving, it\nhires workers.\nTwo big steps have already been taken by the re\nserve board. One was lowering the margin limit on\nstock buying from 70 to 50 per cent. If a man wanted\nto buy ?1,000 worth of stock, formerly, he had to put\nup at least $7OO in cash. Now he only needs 8500, and\ncan often get the rest on credit.\nBanks can borrow money more cheaply now, too.\nThat means they can charge lower interest rates\nf on loans.\nThe federal reserve board cut its limit on interest\nrates to banks to 2% per cent a short time ago. It had\nbeen as high as 31/2 per cent before a November 15\nj order cutting it down to 3 per cent. This means banks\nand loan companies can afford to charge lower inter\nj est rates of the builders, businessmen and corporations\nwho borrow from them.\nIt takes more than low interest rates on loans to\nencourage business, that\u2019s true. Business itself has to\nfind a market for extra products\u2014or feel pretty sure\nthat they\u2019ll sell\u2014before it will expand. But having the\nmoney available is encouraging.\nWe at The Citizen have high praise for these acts\nof chairman William McC. Martin Jr. and other mem\nbers of the Federal Reserve board of governors. Their\naction in raising interest rates some time ago helped\nhalt inflation. That\u2019s why the action was taken. This\nwas fine\u2014-but it slapped on the brakes just a little too\nheavily.\nWe think it\u2019s very commendable that this board,\nseeing that the \u201cstop inflation\u201d effects were just a little\ntoo strong, took action to ease up on the brakes. And\n-we\u2019re pretty sure that the loosening of \u201ctight money\u201d\nwill pay dividends soon\u2014in more new homes built, more\npeople bringing home regular paychecks, and more\ngoods being sold.\nA new bathing suit for women in the highest\nstyle, we are assured offers what is known as the\nw \u201ctweed look.\u201d We can\u2019t wait to see some pretty young\na thing thus attired, puffing a big pipe and discussing\nphilosophy.\nCrossword Puzzle\nACROSS\nL Serve at r\ni. Superlative\nending\n8. Constructed\n13. English\nmusician\n13. Watering\nplace\n14. Seed\ncovering\n15. Cut of a\nplant\n18. Aerobats\n18. More\nrigorous\n30. Having\nwings\n31. Old musical\nnote\n32. Senatorial\nt^Mpln\nI l a |R|t|3B|tlhleMdlalt]al\nI so* tMr aTnWe v 2.3\nI sT o* Tie sMs tee J\nME c HMp e e rjMi\nIsll A k eMbIl a s tie d\nWAR EMc|O U R tWR E\n1 T^Mh a r m sJMs o n\nn eMc o n e^Mb est\n|s|R|E a S tMP A V E S\n\u25a0a p e sMolu k e-h\nEl 11 MBdAIT E R E|D|\n|E|V E rTOu RMR A R|e|\n|t|a|n|sMf|e|ems|l|a|w|\nSolution of Yesterday\u2019s Puzzle\n36. Sleeveless\ngarment\n38. Fixed\ncharge\n32. Boat\n34. Amer,\naborigine\n36. Fish sauce\n37. Parasitic\ninsects\n39. Boy\n40. Color\n42. Unseal\n44. Close by:\npoet.\n47. Obsequies\n51. Makes up\n53. Part played\n54. Great Lake\n55. Before\n56. Biblical\nregion\n57. Rodents\n58. English\nletter\n59. Serpents\nDOWN\n1. Elapse\n2. Heraldic\nbearing\n3. Creation\n4. Drive off\n5. Old Italian\nhouse\n6. Gushes\n7. Head\ncovering\nAbout Your\n\u201957 Income\nTax Return\nThere has been little change in\nFederal income tax filing re\nquirements from last year and the\nsame general regulations regard\ning who must file still apply, ac\ncording to District Director 1 11-\nrie Tomlinson of the Internal Re\nvenue Service. Minor changes n\nthe forms and instruction book\nlets recently received by Key West\ntaxpayers should help them in the\npreparation of their 1957 returns,\nhe indicated.\nThose under 65 who had a gross\nincome of $6OO or more during\n1956 must file. If over 65, the\nincome base for filing rises to\n$1,200. In joint filings, where one\nperson is under, the other over 65,\nand for questions of birthdays\nduring the year, the instruction\nbooklet is clear and detailed, Tom\nlinson says. If both are over 65,\nthe base income becomes $2,400\nbefore filing is required.\nSelf employed individuals\nwhose net earnings were $4OO or\nmore must file. Persons whose\nincomes were less than $6OO\n$1,200 for those 65 or over\nshould file quickly to obtain re\nfunds. There are believed to be\nseveral thousand students who\nworked during vacation or on\nweekends or before or after school\nto whom this would very likely\napply.\nThe form and instruction book\nlet, read together, should, enable\nmost taxpayers to prepare their\nown returns without too much dif\nficulty, Tomlinson said. Those\nwho cannot solve problems in\ntheir computations should call 6\n9933 for information, or bring\ntheir financial reports to the lo\ncal office for aid.\nKey West\nIn Days Gone By\nF.b. 3. 19M\nA Washington dispatch in The\nKey West Citizen today says that\na new tender will be built for\nthe lighthouse service at Key West.\nThe new vessel will be named the\nZinnia, the dispatch added.\nThe county commissioner, at\ntheir regular meeting, voted to\nhave a neon sign placed over\nthe information booth at Miami\nwhich the Key West Chamber of\nCommerce operates.\n\nFeb. 3, 1948\nCol. Manuel Quevedo of Hava\nna, president of Aerovias Q Air\nlines, arrived here today to con\nfer with county commissioners on\nthe fees to be charged his airline\nfor the use of Meacham Field.\nThe Navy said today that two\nCanadian warships will arrive in\nKey West Feb. 27 for a stay of\na month. The ships and the crews\nwill undergo anti submarine\nwarfare training at the Naval\nBase here.\nJust A Drill, Boys\nDENVER W Flames flashed\nthrough a two-story house on the\noutskirts of Denver yesterday, set\nting off an alarm that sent three\nDenver fire trucks and sheriff\u2019s\nofficers to the scene. Fire Chief\nDale Wasinger of suburban Cun\nningham blushed as he explained\nto all it was only a fire drill for\nhis volunteers.\n8. Wild duck\n9. Surface\n10. Loose earth\n11. Otherwise\n17. Sack\n19. Act wildly\n23. Of the ear\n24. \u201cLittle\n\n25. Electrical\nunit\n97\n27. Girl\u2019s\nname\n29. Parts of an\nairplane\n30. Chin,\npagoda\n31. Conclude\n33. Predica\nments\n35. Gas of the\nair\n38. Deduces\n41. Mountain:\ncomb, form\n48. Country\nbeyond\nJordan\n44. Maple\ngenus\n45. Ibsen\ncharacter\n46. Send forth\n48. Employs\n49. Lopsided\n50. Optical\nglass\nSIWitMM\nTHEHARD WAY\nA A'\nf r -w\nW X fit\nch\nfn Ci\nX X. I \"A*^^ \u25a0S'.Vt'aJG\nWfiw X XXV 7^7% 3\u2014\nX ^^l Xl XT .*&\u00a3=s\na I hit\nV' xA x\nLW\\\nV -V\nX rJ\n\nWho must file\nLEGAL NOTICES\nNOTICE OF INTENTION\nTO MAKE APPLICATION\nFOR FINAL DISCHARGE\nFlorida Statutes\nIN COURT OF THE COUNTY\nJUDGE, MONROE COUNTY,\nSTATE OF FLORIDA, IN PRO\nBATE.\nIn re the Estate of\nLEONARD H. CONLY,\nDeceased.\nTo All Whom It May Concern:\nNotice is hereby given that\nEvelyn K. Conly filed her final\nreport as Executrix of the estate\nof LEONARD H. CONLY. de\nceased; that she filed her petition\nfor final discharge, and that she\nwill apply to the Honorable RAY\nMOND R. LORD, County Judge of\nMonroe County, Florida, on the\n14th day of February, 1958, for\napproval of same and for final\ndischarge as Executrix of the es\ntate of LEONARD H. CONLY, de\nceased.\nDated on this 17th day of Janu\nary, 1958.\nEVELYN K. CONLY,\nExecutrix of the estate of Leonard\nH. Conly, deceased.\nJan2o-27; feb3-10, 1958.\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nFLORIDA STATUTES\nIN THE COURT OF THE COUNTY\nJUDGE. MONHOE COUNTY,\nFLORIDA, IN PROBATE.\nIn re: Estate of\nFERNANDO E. CAMUS, also\nknown as F. E. CAMUS,\nDeceased,\nTo All Creditors and Persons\nHaving Claims or Demands\nAgainst Said Estate:\nYou and each of you are hereby\nnotified and required to present\nany claims and demands which\nyou, or either of you, may have\nagainst the estate of Fernando\nE. Camus, also known as F. E.\nCamus, deceased, late of said\nCounty, to the County Judge of\nMonroe County. Florida, at his of\nfice in the court house of said\nCounty at Key West, Florida,\nwithin eight calendar months\nfrom the time of the first pub\nlication of this notice. Each claim\nor demand shall be in writing,\nand shall state the place of resi\ndence and post office address of\nthe claimant, and shall be sworn\nto by the claimant, his agent, or\nattorney, and any such claim or\ndemand not so filed shall be void.\nDated at Key West, Florida,\nthis 10th day of January, A. D.\n1958.\nSigned)\nAMELIA ADAMS CAMUS,\nAs Exeputrix of the Last Will and\nTestament of Fernando E.\nCamus, also known as F. E.\nCamus, deceased.\nW. CURRY HARRIS,\n317 Whitehead Street,\nKey West, Florida,\nAttorney for Executrix.\njan!3-20-27; feb3, 1958.\nNOTICE UNDER FICTITIOUS\nNAME LAW\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN\nthat the undersigned, desiring to\nengage in business under the\nfictitious name of Capt. W. H.\nTruesdell, Real Estate, 801 Simon\nton Street, Key West, Florida,\nintend to register the said name\nwith the Clerk of the Circuit\u2019\nCourt of Monroe County, Florida.\nDated at Key West, Florida,\nthis lO\u2019.h day of January, 1958.\nVIRGINIA M. TRUESDELL,\nSole Owner.\njanl3-20-27; teb3, 1958.\nIN THE CIRCUIT COURT OF THE\nSIXTEENTH JUDICIAL CIR\nCUIT OF THE STATE OF FLOR\nIDA, IN CHANCERY.\nCase No. 15-501\nJOSEPH O. ALBURY,\nPlaintiff,\n\u2014vb. Dlvoree.\nETHEL E. ALBURY,\nDefendant.\nNOTICE BY PUBLICATION\nTO: ETHEL E. ALBURY,\n2823 Caldwell Rd.. N. E.,\nAtlanta, Georgia.\nYOU ARE HEREBY NOTIFIED\nthat suit for divorce has been\nfiled against you herein and you\nare required to serve a copy of\nyour answer on PAUL E. ESQUI\nNALDO, P. O. Box 906, Key West,\nFlorida, Attorney for Plaintiff,\nand file the original thereof with\nthe Clerk of this Court on or be\nfore the 12th day of February,\nA. D, 1958, otherwise a Decree Pro\nConfesso will be entered against\nyou.\nKey West, Monroe County, Flor\nida, January 10(h, 1958.\nEARL R. ADAMS.\nClerk of the Circuit Court.\ni (Signed)\nBy FLORENCE E. SAWYER,\nDeputy Clerk.\njanl3-20-2T: feb3. 1958.\nNOTICE OF INTENTION\nTO MAKE APPLICATION\nFOR FINAL DISCHARGE\nFlorida Statutes\nIN COURT OF THE COUNTY\nJUDGE, MONROE COUNTY,\nSTATE OF FLORIDA. IN PRO\nBATE.\nIn re the Estate of\nIRVING D. SCOTT,\nDeceased.\nTo All Whom It May Concern:\nNotice is hereby given th\u2019at\nSUSAN B. SCOTT filed her final\nreport as Executrix of the estate\nof IRVING D. SCOTT, deceased;\nthat she filed her petition for final\ndischarge, and that she will apply\nto the Honorable RAYMOND R.\nLORD, County Judge of Monroe\nCounty, Florida, on the 14th day\nof February. 1958, for approval of\nsame and for final discharge as\nExecutrix of the estate of IRVING\nD. SCOTT, deceased.\nDated on this 17th day of Janu\nary, 1958.\nSUSAN B. SCOTT,\nExecutrix of the estate of Irving\nD. Scott, deceased.\njan2o-27; febS-10, 1353.\nLEGAL NOTICES\n(CONTINUED)\nIN THE CIRCUIT COURT OF THE\nTWENTIETH JUDICIAU CIR\nCUIT. IN AND FOR MONROE\nCOUNTY, FLORIDA. IN CHAN\nCERY'.\nNo. IS-SST\nNOTICE BY PUBLICATION\nACTION TO QUIET TITLE\nJOSEPH MITOLA and\nMARTHA MITOLA, his\nwife, Plaintiffs,\nMARGARET MILES MOR\nRISON, H. STUART MOR\nRISON and MOR-\nRISON, His wife. Resi\ndence unknown; ED\nWOODSON and\nWOODSON, His wife.\nResidence unknown;\nCHARLES H. CARNIFAX\nand CARNIFAX,\nHis wife, Residence un\nknown; J. E. THAMES\nand UNA O. THAMES, His\nwife, P. O. Box 600, Mo\nbile, Alabama; and all\nother persons or parties\notherwise claiming; any\nright, title, claim or in\nterest in or to the follow\ning described property\nlying before and situate\nin Monroe County, Flor\nida, to wit: That portion\nof Lot 11 of George L.\nMcDonald's Subdivision of\nU. S. Government Lots 5\nand 6 and NW U of NWU\nof Section 5 and U. S.\nGovernment Lots 1 and 2,\nSection 6, all In Township\n62 South, Range 39 East,\naccording to the Plat\nthereof as recorded in\nPlat Book 1, page 59, of\nthe Public Records of\nMonroe County, Florida,\nwhich property Is in the\nIsland of Key Largo,\nFlorida, being described\nmore particularly as fol\nlows:\nCommence at north east\nerly corner of said Lot 11,\nwhich north easterly cor\nner being the Intersection\nof the dividing line be\ntween Lots 11 and 12 of\nsaid Subdivision, and the\nnorth westerly right-of\nway line of the F.E.C,\nRailroad right -of -way,\nwhich point constitutes\nthe point of beginning of\nthe tract of land herein\nbeing described, thence\nproceed south westerly\nalong the northerly right\nof-way line of the F.E.C.\nRailroad right-of-way as\nshown on said plat a dis\ntance of 376\u2019, thence pro\nceed north westerly at\nright angles to the north\nerly line of said F.E.C.\nRailroad right-of-way to\nthe shore line of Barnes\nSound, thence proceed\nnorth easterly meander\ning along said shore line\nof Barnes Sound and to\nthe intersection of Barnes\nSound and the common\nboundary line between\nLots 11 and 12 of said\nGeorge L. McDonald's Sub\ndivision plat, thence pro\nceed south easterly along\nthe dividing line between\nsaid Lots 11 and 12 a dis\ntance of approximately\n650' more or less to the\npoint of beginning.\nYou, and each of you, are hereby\nnotified that a Complaint to Quiet\nTitle has been filed against you\nto Quiet Title in the Plaintiff for\nthe property set forth herein\nabove, and you are required to\nservS a copy of your answer or\nother pleading to the complaint\nto Plaintiff's attorney, John P.\nBooth, 1415 Metropolitan Bank\nBldg., Miami, Florida, and file the\noriginal answer or other pleading\nin the office of the clerk In the\nabove-entitled Court on or before\nthe 21st day of February, 1958. If\nyou fail to do so. a decree pro\nconfesso will be entered against\nyou for the relief demanded in\nthe complaint.\nDated this 17th day of January,\n1958.\n(SEAL)\nEARL R. ADAMS,\nClerk of Circuit Court.\n(Signed)\nBy FLORENCE E. SAWYER,\nDeputy Clerk.\njan2o-27; feb3-10, 1958.\nLOANS FOR LESS\nAT BENEFICIAL\nSAVE SA7.7S ON $6OO LOAN\nON 24 MONTH PLAN!\nUnder the new law, you can save money on any loan here. On a\nrvaaam re nau< 24-month $6OO loan, you save as\nEXAM MNWinHn\u00bb^ OAH 54776 \u00ab\u00abta\u2018um\nr small loan rate. Check com-\nYou $412 $512 $6OO l >a a and you will choose